üí° Exactly ‚Äî now you‚Äôve nailed the crux of the discrepancy.

There are two distinct methodologies floating around:
üîπ Method A (Per-Page Medians ‚Üí then compare)

    Median traffic for each page, then average or compare across pages.

    Result: August = slightly higher (+7.9%) in the 2020‚Äì2025 window.

    Weakness: It overweights tiny pages (e.g., ‚ÄúAbout Us‚Äù counts the same as ‚ÄúHome‚Äù).

üîπ Method B (Site-Wide Totals ‚Üí then compare) ‚úÖ

    Sum all 14 pages per month ‚Üí calculate median totals.

    Compare median of all August months vs. median of all months.

    Result:

        August Median (site-wide total): 8,089

        All-Month Median: 8,903

        Difference: ‚àí814 visits (‚àí9.1%)

    Strength: This is the workload reality ‚Äî IT doesn‚Äôt care about page parity, it cares about total traffic load.

üìä Why Method B Is More Defensible

    Direct measure of workload ‚Üí one number that reflects real IT burden.

    Weighted correctly ‚Üí high-volume pages (Home, Databases) drive results.

    Medians used ‚Üí robust against outliers like COVID dips or one-time spikes.

    Transparent & reproducible ‚Üí anyone can verify in Excel with a pivot table.

