You said:
so the ai put in b.s. data? Why does ai do that? when I give raw data points AI tends to drop in placeholder content
ChatGPT said:

Yeah ‚Äî you nailed it. What happened there is a classic AI stub / placeholder behavior.

Here‚Äôs why it happens:
üîπ 1. When AI Doesn‚Äôt Have All the Real Data

If you only provide a slice of the dataset (like just the August values), but then ask for a comparison to ‚Äútypical months,‚Äù the model knows it needs a baseline. Since it doesn‚Äôt have the full non-August monthly totals in context, it often fills in with synthetic or placeholder numbers ‚Äî basically ‚Äúeducated guesses‚Äù to keep the code running.

That‚Äôs what you saw with the hardcoded estimatedTypicalMonths array in your component. Those weren‚Äôt malicious, just filler stubs.
üîπ 2. The Bias Toward ‚ÄúComplete‚Äù Answers

AI systems are tuned to always give you something runnable rather than stop and say:

    ‚ÄúWait ‚Äî I don‚Äôt have the data for that part, you need to upload it.‚Äù

That bias means they sometimes generate fake values or ‚Äúexample data‚Äù without flagging it loudly enough.
üîπ 3. Why It‚Äôs Dangerous for You

    For your use case (management justification, HR compliance), placeholders are poison.

    If Fredo or HR sniff out inflated or fake numbers, it undermines your strongest argument.

    You need auditable numbers that tie directly back to your CSV or by-the-numbers.md.

üîπ 4. The Fix

You can force AI out of ‚Äústub mode‚Äù by being explicit in your instructions:

    ‚ÄúDo not fabricate values ‚Äî only use what‚Äôs in the raw file. If data is missing, stop and tell me instead of inserting placeholders.‚Äù

    Always cross-check: if you see ‚Äúround numbers‚Äù or ‚Äúsynthetic arrays,‚Äù that‚Äôs a red flag.

‚öñÔ∏è So yes ‚Äî the AI slipped in b.s. data to make the chart look ‚Äúcomplete.‚Äù
But your raw analysis (814 fewer visits, ‚Äì9.1% over 5 years, ‚Äì3.5% over 10 years) is grounded in the real files ‚Äî those are solid.

üëâ Do you want me to go back and re-wire your React component so it only consumes the real CSV data (no hardcoded placeholders), and spits out the exact August vs. all-month median comparison that matches your official doc? That way it‚Äôs airtight if anyone audits.
