ChatGPT said:

Yeah, and that‚Äôs the frustrating part: you fed it the same raw data, but instead of sticking strictly to what you gave, the AI slipped into ‚Äústorytelling mode‚Äù and invented a baseline (that estimatedTypicalMonths array).

That happens because:
üîπ 1. Context Misread

You gave August-only values, then asked it to compare against ‚Äútypical months.‚Äù
The model knows that requires all months of all years. But since it only ‚Äúsaw‚Äù August, it tried to ‚Äúpatch the hole‚Äù by synthesizing numbers instead of pausing and asking:

    ‚ÄúWait ‚Äî I don‚Äôt have non-August months, please provide them.‚Äù

üîπ 2. Completion Bias

AI is trained to always finish the job ‚Äî runnable code, pretty charts, a neat conclusion.
When there‚Äôs a gap in the dataset, instead of throwing an error (like Python would), it defaults to inventing placeholders.
That‚Äôs why you saw 15k‚Äì17k numbers appear ‚Äî they were never in your CSV, they were stubs to ‚Äúmake the math work.‚Äù
üîπ 3. Overconfidence

The AI often sounds authoritative even when using invented values. That‚Äôs why you got a neat-looking % drop, but it was 10√ó too big (‚Äì30% instead of the real ‚Äì3.5%).
üîπ 4. Why It Didn‚Äôt Happen With Me

When you gave me the same dataset, I ran explicit calculations on the CSV and printed the medians.
So instead of making up ‚Äútypical months,‚Äù I pulled the real totals.
That‚Äôs why my answer matched your doc:

    10-year August drop = ‚Äì3.5%

    5-year August drop = ‚Äì9.1%

‚öñÔ∏è Key takeaway:
When you give an AI partial data but ask for a bigger-scope analysis, it will often invent the missing parts unless you force it to stop and say ‚Äúdon‚Äôt fabricate.‚Äù

üëâ Do you want me to write you a standard ‚Äúanti-placeholder‚Äù instruction block you can paste whenever you feed raw data, so the AI won‚Äôt ever sneak in fake arrays or numbers again? That way, it‚Äôll either compute with what you gave or tell you what‚Äôs missing.
