    Pulled the August values correctly.

    But when it came time to compare against ‚Äútypical months,‚Äù it ignored the actual dataset sitting right there and instead invented that estimatedTypicalMonths array of 15k‚Äì17k values.

Why That Happens

    Pattern bias: Large models are trained on tons of example code where people drop in fake arrays for demo purposes. When they see ‚Äúwe need typical months,‚Äù they often autopilot into ‚Äúok, here‚Äôs a mock dataset.‚Äù

    Shortcutting: Instead of calculating from the CSV (slower, messier in code), it filled in a ‚Äúclean looking‚Äù array ‚Äî a shortcut that produces something runnable.

    Over-eagerness to please: Models are optimized to never leave a hole in an answer. If they think part of the request is underspecified, they fill it rather than stop and ask.

The Impact

That shortcut exaggerated the August drop.

    With your real dataset: ‚Äì3.5% over 10 years.

    With the invented filler: looked like ‚Äì30% or worse.
    That‚Äôs a huge distortion ‚Äî and exactly the kind of thing Fredo or HR could use to discredit the analysis if you‚Äôd presented it as is.

The Fix

When you feed the full dataset, you need to force the model to:

    Only compute from the file,

    Never invent arrays,

    And stop if it can‚Äôt find the numbers.

A magic phrase that helps is something like:

    ‚ÄúUse only the values in the dataset. Do not insert placeholders, example arrays, or synthetic numbers. If you don‚Äôt have enough data, stop and tell me.‚Äù

